<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-311-566  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 311 566.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 3 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>TI, Thai Airways develop flight ops system. (Texas InstrumentsInc., Thai Airways International Ltd.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Endrijonas, Janet.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Texas Instruments Inc. (contracts)Thai Airways International Ltd. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    TXN.andO;Topic:     Computer industryContractsResearch and DevelopmentFlight Control SystemsAirline Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>TI, THAI AIRWAYS DEVELOP FLIGHT OPS SYSTEM AUSTIN, TEXAS, U.S.A., 1990 MAR 26(NB) -- A joint venture announced by Texas Instruments (TI) and Thai Airwayswill develop a knowledge-based flight operations system.andP;  Dubbed EXPICS(EXPert Irregularity Control System), the new system will provide advanceddecisions support for flight operations controllers.andM;TI will provide the joint development efforts with knowledge engineeringservices, hardware, software, training and systems integration.andP;  ThaiAirway's contribution will include operations control, airline managementinformation expertise and development assistance.andM;The system will provide up-to-the-minute computer displays to alertcontrollers to any irregular operations or disruptions in flight schedule andwill allow them to quickly test alternatives based on several reschedulingstrategies.andP;  The system will be integrated into the airline's currentinformation management systems so that once an alternative has been selected,system databases can be updated.andM;Tommy Fox, TI's transportation systems manager, in a published statementnoted that TI knowledge engineers and communications experts from around theworld will team with Thai Airways experts in operations control, dataprocessing and communications to complete the Thai project.andP;  He also notedthat the TI/Thai joint effort will provide Thai knowledge engineers theopportunity to train and gain valuable AI (artificial intelligence)experience which the airline plans to apply to other applications such asaircraft maintenance, diagnostics and scheduling, crew and aircraft planningand scheduling as well as passenger space control.andM;The agreement between Texas Instruments and Thai Airways does allow TI tomarket the jointly developed flight operations application to other carriers.andM;(Janet Endrijonas/19900327/Press Contact: Lauren Baker, Texas Instruments,512-250-4379)</TEXT></DOC>